2500|$|During the 16th {{and early}} 17th centuries in Europe, the <b>transverse</b> <b>flute</b> was {{available}} in several sizes, in effect forming a consort {{in much the same}} way recorders and other instruments were used in consorts. At this stage, the <b>transverse</b> <b>flute</b> was usually made in one section (or two for the larger sizes) and had a cylindrical bore. As a result, this flute had a rather soft sound and limited range and was used primarily in compositions for the [...] "soft consort".|$|E
