25|$|Usually in D, wooden <b>transverse</b> <b>flutes</b> {{were played}} in European {{classical}} music {{mainly in the}} period from the early 18th century to the early 19th century. As such the instrument is often indicated as baroque flute. Gradually marginalized by the Western concert flute in the 19th century, baroque flutes were again played from the late 20th century {{as part of the}} historically informed performance practice.|$|R
50|$|Other {{versions}} of BWV 1027 exist: {{there is a}} trio sonata for two <b>transverse</b> <b>flutes</b> and continuo (BWV 1039); {{as well as a}} trio sonata for organ in three movements. Russell Stinson has determined that the organ work, with the first two movements transcribed from BWV 1039/i and BWV 1039/ii and the last from BWV 1027/iv, is not by Bach but most probably by Johann Peter Kellner.|$|R
